Introduction

This tutorial provides a step-by-step guide for analyzing RNA sequencing data when a reference genome is available. The workflow includes quality control of reads, trimming, alignment to the reference genome, conversion of aligned data to raw counts, differential expression analysis using DESeq2, and annotation of reads with BioMart. Unless otherwise specified, the steps will be conducted on the Galaxy server (but you can install the tools on your system for doing it quicker, see my guide for setting up your system).

Important: Please review the lecture slides available on our Moodle (Campus Virtual) platform before starting this tutorial. It is also necessary to understand our training in databases and introductory bioinformatics lessons.

The data we will be using are comparative transcriptomes of chlamydomonas grown at either ambient or cold (4ºC) temperature. Each condition was done in triplicate, giving us a total of six samples we will be working with, as these samples are paired we will work with 12 files. These files are part of Dr. Carbó doctoral work and resulting paper is still unpublised. You can find a paper describing culture conditions here. Furthermore in this pack of files you will find the Chlamydomonas genome version 6 (CreinhardtiiCC_4532_707_v6.0.fa.gz), transcriptome (CreinhardtiiCC_4532_707_v6.1.transcript.fa.gz) and annotations (CreinhardtiiCC_4532_707_v6.1.gene_exons.gff3.gz). This version of the genome has been contributed by Craig et al.(2022).

Knowing our genome and annotation

The latest Chlamydomonas reinhardtii v6 genome assembly consists of 17 chromosomes, representing its main linear DNA molecules, and numerous contigs, which are smaller DNA fragments that could not yet be fully assembled into chromosomes. Furthermore there is an special contig, mating_type_plus, those sequences characteristic of MT+ (genome was over MT-), and chloroplast and mitochondrial genomes.

Description of the columns of a GFF3 file:

Column Description
Sequence ID The name of the sequence (e.g., chromosome, contig, scaffold) where the feature is located.
Source The source of the feature annotation (e.g., "Phytozome", "Ensembl," "GeneMark").
Feature Type The type of genomic feature (e.g., "gene," "exon," "CDS," "mRNA").
Start The starting position of the feature on the sequence (1-based coordinates).
End The ending position of the feature on the sequence (1-based coordinates).
Score A numerical value indicating the feature's confidence or significance (use . if not provided).
Strand The DNA strand on which the feature is located (+ for positive, - for negative, or . if unknown).
Phase Reading frame for coding sequences: 0 (start at codon), 1/2 (offsets), or . for non-coding features.
Attributes Additional details as key-value pairs (e.g., ID=gene1;Name=ABC;Parent=mRNA1).

Second step: quality control

A commonly used tool for assessing sequence quality is FastQC, which offers a comprehensive set of modular analyses to identify potential issues in your data before proceeding with downstream analyses. For instance, it can be used to detect the presence of known adapters in the sequences. In this tutorial, we will use FastQC to analyze the quality of the provided FASTQ file.

You must conduct it for all of your samples, either in this form or as a part of data collection (we will later go through that). HTML reports will be created.

Manually reviewing multiple QC reports and comparing results across samples can be tedious. To simplify this process, having all QC plots consolidated on a single page is highly beneficial, making it easier to identify trends in the data. MultiQC is a tool specifically designed for this purpose. It aggregates individual QC reports and compiles them into a single, comprehensive, and user-friendly report.

Here is an example of the command-line syntax for the tools mentioned if you prefer to do out of Galaxy environment:
fastqc seqfile_1 seqfile_2 _1 and _2, left and right reads, respectively
multiqc data/*_fastqc.zip

Interpretation of FastQC reports

FastQC reports are essential for assessing the quality of sequencing data and ensuring its suitability for downstream analyses. Key sections to interpret include sequence quality scores, GC content distribution, adapter content, and duplication levels. Each section is flagged with a pass (green), warning (orange), or fail (red), providing a clear visual indicator of potential issues. If warnings or failures are flagged, appropriate corrective actions, such as trimming low-quality bases, removing adapter contamination, or filtering problematic reads, can be taken. Proper interpretation of FastQC reports ensures clean, reliable data for accurate alignment and analysis:

  1. Per Base Quality Scores: Assesses read quality across the sequence length. High-quality scores (green) indicate good data, while drops in quality (orange/red) may require trimming.
    • Problem: Low-quality scores at the 3′ or 5′ ends of reads.
    • Solution: Trim low-quality bases using tools like Trimmomatic, Cutadapt, or fastp.
  2. Per Sequence Quality Scores: Identifies if most reads are of high quality or if there’s a significant number of low-quality reads.
    • Problem: Many low-quality reads overall.
    • Solution: Filter out low-quality reads using a minimum quality threshold (e.g., Phred score >20) with trimming tools.
  3. Adapter Content: Detects contamination from sequencing adapters; high levels may require trimming.
    • Problem: High adapter contamination in reads.
    • Solution: Remove adapters using tools like Cutadapt or the adapter removal module in Trimmomatic.
  4. Per Base Sequence Content: Checks for GC bias or sequence composition issues, which can indicate technical problems or contamination.
    • Problem: Imbalance in nucleotide composition, especially early in the read.
    • Solution: If specific biases are consistent (e.g., Illumina sequencing), this may not require action. Otherwise, investigate possible contamination.
  5. Sequence Duplication Levels: Indicates duplication rates; high duplication might suggest PCR bias or low library diversity.
    • Problem: High duplication rates indicating over-amplification or low library complexity. Be careful about
    • Solution: Remove duplicate reads if they are likely artifacts, using tools like fastp or PRINSEQ.
  6. Overrepresented Sequences: Flags highly abundant sequences, which could signal contamination or artifacts.
    • Problem: High abundance of specific sequences (e.g., contaminants or primer dimers).
    • Solution: Use tools like fastp or BBTools to identify and remove contaminant sequences.
  7. GC Content: lala
    • Problem: Unusual GC distribution compared to expected values.
    • Solution: Investigate for contamination or sequencing artifacts. If specific contamination is identified, remove affected reads.

General Recommendations:

  1. Re-run FastQC after cleanup to confirm improvements.
  2. Document changes to ensure reproducibility of the preprocessing steps.
  3. If problems persist after trimming or filtering, consider revisiting sample preparation protocols to address issues at the source.

Third step: trimming of adaptors and low quality bases

Trimming RNA-seq reads is a crucial preprocessing step in transcriptomics to remove adapter sequences, low-quality bases, and other technical artifacts introduced during sequencing. This process improves the accuracy of read alignment to the reference genome or transcriptome, reduces errors in gene expression quantification, and minimizes biases caused by contamination or degraded sequences. By enhancing the overall quality of the reads, trimming ensures reliable and reproducible downstream analyses, such as differential expression and transcript assembly, while reducing computational errors and optimizing the performance of analysis tools.

Using TrimGalore!

We will use Trim Galore!, a versatile tool for preprocessing RNA-seq and other sequencing data, combining Cutadapt for adapter removal and FastQC for quality control. It trims low-quality bases, removes adapter sequences, and ensures clean, high-confidence reads for accurate downstream analysis as we explained above.

Please use the following settings:
Is this library paired- or single-end? Paired-end
Introduce the matching left _1and right _2files and proceed with default settings. You need to repeat this step for all six samples.

Rename the file, for example, from "Trim Galore! on data 2 and data 1: trimmed reads pair 1" to "Trim Galore! on Chlamy_0h_01_1" (or a name corresponding to the specific file). This will make it easier to identify and organize your files.

Here is an example of the command-line syntax for the tools mentioned:
trim_galore --paired --retain_unpaired --phred33 --length 36 -q 20 --stringency 1 -e 0.1 --cores 38 -o ./trimmed_sequences /Ruta_fichero_R1 /ruta_fichero_R2
Notice that you can use or not the --retain_unpaired argument. This was not set up in Galaxy environment. Please refer to classrom slides to get more information.

The program will return paired validated sequences (with the suffix _val) and unpaired sequences (with the suffix _unpaired), along with log files and statistics. The resulting files are saved in .gz format.

Questions:

1. Why do we run the trimming tool only once on a paired-end dataset and not separately for each file? The trimming tool processes paired-end datasets together to ensure consistency between the read pairs. If one or both reads in a pair become too short during trimming (e.g., below the specified length cutoff), the tool removes the entire pair. However, reads that meet the length threshold but have a partner that becomes too short can optionally be saved as single-end reads. This approach prevents data loss while maintaining the integrity of the paired-end structure, ensuring that only high-quality reads are retained for further analysis.
2. Was the adapter contamination problem solved? To answer this question you must open the multiQC report, and look for the adapter content plot. As you will see after finding this representation, the samples showed no traces of adaptors in the last bases of our reads. So yes, this problem was controled.
3. Should we continue pre-processing our reads considering we have red flag in per base content and in sequence duplication? Given the context that the samples are from Chlamydomonas reinhardtii, a species with high GC content, and that a high level of transcript duplication is expected due to abundant photosynthetic gene transcripts, it is likely that the red flags in per base content and sequence duplication are biological rather than technical artifacts. Here's how to address the question:

Per Base Content: Chlamydomonas' high GC content may naturally lead to deviations in the per base content plot. This is typical for such organisms and may not warrant additional preprocessing unless there is evidence of adapter contamination or low-quality reads in the flagged regions. As the adapter content and quality scores in the FastQC report are acceptable, no further trimming is needed.

Sequence Duplication: High sequence duplication in Chlamydomonas is expected, especially for highly expressed photosynthetic genes. This is a biological feature rather than a technical issue. Duplication flagged as "high" does not require actions.

Consequently, further preprocessing is likely unnecessary, keeping in mind that the flags are consistent with the biological characteristics of your samples.
4. Should we continue pre-processing our reads considering we have orange flag in sequence length distribution? Yes, this is not a cause for concern. The original samples received a green flag, indicating that the reads had consistent lengths. However, the variability in read lengths observed now is a result of trimming, where low-quality bases or adapter sequences were removed. This truncation is a normal outcome of preprocessing steps and is commonly seen in RNA-seq workflows. Such differences in read length do not indicate a problem and are expected when ensuring high-quality reads for downstream analysis.

However, if trimming has not been performed, a warning about sequence length distribution may indicate inconsistent read lengths resulting from poor library preparation, sequencing errors, or instrument-specific artifacts. In such cases, further investigation is needed to identify and address the underlying issue.

Fourth step: mapping

To interpret the reads, we first need to identify their genomic origins to determine which genes they correspond to. This is achieved by aligning or "mapping" the reads to a reference genome or transcriptome, provided one is available for the organism being studied. Mapping involves finding the most likely location of each read in the genome or a particular transcript, which can be challenging due to the repetitive nature of some sequences and the potential presence of sequencing errors or variations such as mutations and insertions. This process is comparable to solving a jigsaw puzzle, where not all pieces are unique, and some may fit in multiple places, requiring computational algorithms to make informed decisions about their placement. Accurate mapping is a critical step in transcriptomics as it directly influences downstream analyses such as gene expression quantification and variant discovery.

Mapping can be performed against either a genome or a transcriptome, depending on the goals of the study:

  • Genome Mapping: Reads are aligned to the entire genome, including both coding and non-coding regions. This approach is useful for identifying novel transcripts, splicing patterns, or unannotated regions, as well as for analyzing genomic variants like mutations or structural rearrangements.

  • Transcriptome Mapping: Reads are aligned only to the annotated transcriptome (a collection of known transcripts), which can streamline the analysis and reduce computational complexity. This is particularly useful when the focus is on quantifying gene expression or identifying isoforms without exploring novel features.

In RNA-seq studies, the choice between genome and transcriptome mapping depends on whether novel discovery or annotation-driven analysis is prioritized. Genome mapping is more comprehensive, while transcriptome mapping is faster and often sufficient for well-annotated species. In this tutorial we will use genome mapping.

Choosing and adequate mapper: RNA Star, HISAT2 and Bowtie2

Bowtie2, RNA STAR and HISAT2 are three of the most employed mappers. HISAT2 and RNA STAR being two of the most widely used options for RNA-seq analysis. HISAT2 is a modern aligner that offers efficient and memory-friendly performance. Compared to Bowtie2, HISAT2 is more recent, slightly faster, and includes advanced features like soft-clipping and spliced read alignment, making it particularly suitable for eukaryotic RNA-seq data. It can accurately handle intron-spanning reads, which is crucial for transcriptome analysis. In contrast, RNA STAR is highly optimized for speed and sensitivity, excelling in detecting complex splicing events and processing large datasets quickly. While HISAT2 is ideal for systems with limited computational resources, RNA STAR is better suited for high-performance environments or large-scale transcriptome studies, particularly when exploring novel splicing patterns. Bowtie2, although reliable for DNA alignments, lacks the ability to process spliced reads, making it less appropriate for RNA-seq.

The choice between HISAT2 and STAR depends on the specific requirements of your RNA-seq analysis, as both aligners have strengths and trade-offs. Here is a comparison to help decide which might be better for your needs:

Feature HISAT2 STAR
Strengths
Efficiency Fast and memory-efficient (<10 GB RAM) Very fast for large RNA-seq datasets
Splicing Supports spliced read alignments and soft-clipping Highly sensitive to complex splicing events
Resource Requirements Ideal for systems with limited computational power Suited for high-performance computing environments
Application Great for moderate to high coverage RNA-seq data Ideal for large-scale transcriptome studies
Detailed Output Good general alignment features Provides splice junctions and multi-mapping reads
Limitations
Sensitivity Lower sensitivity to complex splicing events Requires high RAM (30–60 GB for large genomes)
Speed Slightly slower for very large datasets Computationally demanding on less powerful systems
  • Use HISAT2 if you prioritize memory efficiency, have limited computational resources, or are conducting routine RNA-seq analysis where extreme sensitivity to splicing is not critical.
  • Use STAR if you have access to high-performance computing resources, need to analyze large, complex datasets quickly, or require high sensitivity for detecting novel splice junctions and alternative splicing.

Reviewing results

Our mappers will produce some logs and BAM files. A BAM (Binary Alignment/Map) file is a compressed, binary format used to store aligned sequencing reads efficiently. It contains detailed information about where each read maps to the reference genome, including the chromosomal coordinates, mapping quality scores, and whether the read aligns uniquely or to multiple locations. BAM files are integral to RNA-seq workflows, as they provide a compact and fast-access format for downstream analyses like transcript quantification, variant calling, and visualization.

We can easily monitor our results employing MultiQC. You can run it with the following parameters:

Which tool was used for generate logs? STAR
Type of STAR output? Log
STAR log output: RNA STAR on collection N: log

or/and

Which tool was used for generate logs? HISAT2
Output of HISAT2: HISAT2 on collection N: Mapping Summary

Furthermore we can use a genome browser, like IGV, and explore our BAM files. To do so:

  1. Install IGV, SeqMonk, or other genome browser locally.
  2. Download entire collection of BAM files (after STAR or HISAT2). It is important that you download entire collection. Is the only way to also get BAI files.
  3. Create a new genome, using CreinhardtiiCC_4532_707_v6.0.fa.gz genome and CreinhardtiiCC_4532_707_v6.1.gene_exons.gff3.gz for annotations.
  4. Load BAM(s) file(s) as track(s).

1. Which information provide blue lines? The presence of the different genes, its introns and exons.
2. Which information provide grey peaks ".bam coverage" track? The coverage plot: the sum of mapped reads at each position. This is proportional to gene expression levels.
3. What do the connecting lines between some of the aligned reads indicate "junctions"? The connecting lines between aligned reads indicate junction events, also known as splice sites. These represent reads that span across introns, aligning to exon-exon boundaries. Such spliced alignments are common in RNA-seq data from eukaryotic organisms, where the mature mRNA is processed by splicing out introns. These lines provide a visual representation of the evidence for splicing in the transcriptome, helping identify exon connectivity and alternative splicing events.

We can investigate more features of our transcriptome for instance using a Sashimi plot. For doing so, in IGV right click over Chlamy BAM file and select Sashimi plot. You should have a look over documentation for understand the plot below:

1. What does the vertical red bar graph represent, and what is the significance of the arcs with numbers? The vertical red bar graph represents the coverage for each alignment track, showing the number of reads aligned to each position in the genome. The arcs represent observed splice junctions, which are reads that span introns and connect two exons.
2. What do the numbers displayed on the arcs represent? The numbers on the arcs indicate the number of reads that support the observed splice junction, providing a quantitative measure of splicing events.
3. Why are there different groups of stacked blue linked boxes at the bottom of the plot? The stacked groups of blue linked boxes at the bottom represent the different transcripts or isoforms of the gene(s) in this region, as annotated in the GTF file. These linked boxes correspond to exons and their connectivity based on the reference gene model.

Checking strandness in RNA-seq data is important because it determines whether the sequencing reads retain information about the strand of the transcript they were derived from. Strand-specific RNA-seq protocols preserve this information, which can significantly enhance the accuracy of downstream analyses. Our data is unstranded, but we can quickly check it in IGV. Just right click over the bam track and check Color Aligments by first-in-pair strand. Then squished if you see some expanded view. As you can see an even number of red and blue reads are plot, indicating the unstrandness of our samples. You can also group aligments by first-in pair, so you can see positive and negative groups.

1. Which tool aligns more reads? Is this important? Despite the results are almost identical, STAR produces slightly better results.

A key metric to evaluate is the percentage of reads successfully mapped to the reference genome. A low mapping rate may indicate problems with the data quality or the analysis process. In this case, over 90% of the reads have mapped across all samples, representing a strong mapping efficiency. Additionally, the majority of these reads have mapped uniquely, meaning they align to a single location in the reference genome rather than multiple locations.
2. Which information do you find in a SAM/BAM file? Which kind of files are .BAI? A SAM/BAM file contains detailed information about sequencing reads and their alignment to a reference genome. Similar to a FASTQ file, it includes the read sequences and their associated quality scores. However, it also provides critical mapping information, such as the genomic location where each read aligns, the mapping quality (a measure of confidence in the alignment), information on whether the read mapped uniquely or to multiple locations, and details on paired-end read relationships. BAM files are the compressed, binary version of SAM files, making them more efficient for storage and processing.

BAI files are index files associated with BAM files. They are essential for tools like genome browsers to quickly access specific regions of a BAM file, enabling efficient visualization and navigation of mapped reads across genomic tracks. Without the BAI file, retrieving and displaying alignment data in genome browsers or for analysis would be significantly slower.

Fifth step: Counting

In Galaxy, the alignment step generates a set of BAM files, each containing the read alignments for a specific sample. Within these BAM files, the chromosomal location of each mapped read is recorded. Having determined the genomic origin of the reads, the next step is to summarize this information at the level of genes or exons. This can be achieved using a tool called featureCounts, which calculates the number of reads mapped to specific genomic features, such as mouse genes, based on a gene annotation file (e.g., our GFF file CreinhardtiiCC_4532_707_v6.1.gene_exons.gff3.gz). The annotation specifies the start and end positions of each exon for every gene, allowing featureCounts to aggregate reads mapped to these regions. Special care is taken with reads spanning exon-exon boundaries or in regions with overlapping annotations to ensure accurate counting (we will face some issues later).

There are alternative counters like HTSeq, StringTie or even the pseudoaligner Salmon. Next table provides an overview of each algorithm's functionality, input requirements, speed, accuracy and output:

Feature HTSeq StringTie FeatureCounts Salmon
Purpose Read counting per gene Transcript assembly and quantification Read counting per feature Transcript-level quantification
Input Aligned reads (BAM/SAM) Aligned reads (BAM) Aligned reads (BAM/SAM) Raw reads (FASTQ) but BAM are also supported
Algorithm Type Rule-based counting Assembly-based quantification Rule-based counting Probabilistic quantification
Transcript Assembly Not performed Performed Not performed Not performed
Strand Specificity Supported Supported Supported Supported
Speed Moderate Slower due to assembly Fast Very fast
Ease of Use Moderate (basic command-line) Moderate (additional complexity for assembly) Easy Easy
Normalization Not built-in Built-in normalization Not built-in Built-in normalization
Accuracy High for gene counts High for transcript-level assembly High for gene counts High for transcript-level quantification
Output Gene-level counts Transcript abundance and assembly Gene/feature-level counts Transcript abundance
Parallelization Limited support Limited support Good support Good support
Annotation Dependency Required (GTF/GFF) Required (GTF/GFF) Required (GTF/GFF) Can work with or without (pseudoalignment mode)
Suitability Gene-level expression analysis Transcript-level expression analysis Feature-level (exons, genes) analysis Transcript and isoform quantification

In this example, we will use featureCounts using many of the default settings, which are optimized for general use cases. For instance, by default, featureCounts only includes reads that uniquely map to the reference genome. This is advantageous for testing differential gene expression, as it ensures that reads are unambiguously assigned to a single genomic location, simplifying interpretation. While featureCounts offers numerous adjustable parameters, understanding their impact requires considerable reading and experimentation. We won’t cover these details here, but you can explore the tool’s documentation or various online tutorials for further guidance.

FeatureCounts tags each read into the following categories:

  1. Assigned: Reads successfully mapped and uniquely assigned to a specific genomic feature (e.g., an exon or gene).
  2. Unassigned: Unmapped: Reads that did not align to the reference genome during the mapping process.
  3. Unassigned: Multimapping: Reads that map to multiple genomic locations, making it unclear where they should be assigned.
  4. Unassigned: No Features: Reads that map to regions of the genome that are not annotated as part of any feature (e.g., intergenic regions).
  5. Unassigned: Ambiguity: Reads that overlap multiple features, such as two genes or isoforms, and cannot be uniquely assigned to one.

Questions

1. Why do we have a lot of reads in the class unassigned:Ambiguity?When featureCounts reports a high number of reads as "ambiguous," it means the tool was unable to assign these reads to a single genomic feature. This often occurs when reads overlap multiple genes or exons, especially in genomes with high gene density or overlapping features as in Chlamydomonas. In our genome annotation file we have several splicing forms which overlaps. Ambiguities can also arise from reads mapping to non-unique regions, such as repetitive sequences, or from complex alternative splicing, where reads align to multiple isoforms. Additionally, paired-end reads may be marked as ambiguous if one read in a pair maps to one gene and its mate maps to another.
2. How can we solve this issue?To address this, ensure the annotation file is accurate and matches the reference genome. Adjusting featureCounts parameters, such as allowing multi-mapping reads (-M) or permitting assignment to overlapping features (-O), can also help, though these may complicate downstream interpretation. Filtering reads prone to ambiguity or performing gene-level analysis instead of transcript-level counting can further mitigate the issue. Repeat previous analyses allowing multi-mapping reads (-M) and largest overlap .
3. Can you tell any difference when considering multimapping in comparion to your first analysis? Now ~75% of reads are assigned to exons. This is a fairly typical number for RNA-seq (65-80% is good).
4. If you look at STAR or HISAT2 results you will find that >95% reads are mapped in al casses, but why featureCounts can only assing 80% of them? The discrepancy arises because STAR or HISAT2 report the percentage of reads that are aligned to the genome or transcriptome, whereas FeatureCounts specifically assigns reads to specific annotated genomic features (e.g., genes, exons).
